AGI -&nbsp;
<span> A recent survey by the National Council of Youth (CNG), carried out in collaboration with the Piepoli Institute, reveals an important picture: at the next European elections 47% of young Italians were said to vote. The figure is positive if it is taken into account that the overall probability is estimated at 45%, with a lower figure for over 54 to 43%.</span>
&nbsp;
Considering that in 2019 participation in the vote was 54.5% and that, instead, from these estimates the overall turnout would seem in decline, confirming a total downward trend in the last 15 years, opposed to the general European trend that has seen increase participation, the figure of youth participation confirms the results of the Eurobarometer survey on the last European elections that show, in fact, as in 2019 the total increase of the turnout in the European generations is determined. In particular, young citizens under 25 years (+14 percentage points on 2014) and 25-39 years (+12 percentage points on 2014), with a total turnout in past European elections of 50.6%, the highest since 1994, with 19 Member States.
&nbsp;
From the study, carried out on a representative sample of the Italian population, it also emerges, as for under 35 the themes addressed in the election campaign do not reflect their concerns and priorities. Only 8% of young people, in fact, are considered very satisfied by the political debate on Europeans, while 6 out of 10 young people believe that the latter is not adequately addressing the criticalities and needs that live.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The figure goes down further if only under 25 are considered, considering the 18-24 sample, in fact, it is only 33% (very + enough) to be satisfied at least in part. Thus, 7 out of 10 young people feel that they are not facing adequate criticality and needs. Given much lower than that of the 35-54 band where the percentage reaches 50%.
&nbsp;
For young people, the topics on which the debate should be directed are, on the other hand, those relating to work and employment (39%), followed, in order of preference, school and university (18%), post-school/university training (18%) for the development of new professional skills, and climate change (9%). This data reveals an urgent need to reorient the focus of political debate towards issues that have a direct impact on the professional future and staff of girls and boys.
&nbsp;
"The data we have found on the intention of voting demonstrate, once again, that are especially young generations to want to contribute to collective choices, not only of our country but also of the European Union, through the exercise of the right to vote. In a percentage, 47%, which would even exceed that of over 54, equal to 43%, and which could thus lead to an increase in overall turn to the next Europeans which would be 45%. For this reason, the figure on youth participation is important, in line with the results of the last European elections, which show that in 2019 the increase of turn to the polls was determined mainly by the participation of the young generations throughout the EU" says the President of the National Council of Youth, Maria Cristina Pisani who adds "It is the demonstration that the young people want to exercise with responsibility their right to vote, even if only 8% of the youth are considered very satisfied work and employment (39%), followed, in order of preference, by school and university (18%) and post-school/university training (18%) for the development of new professional skills, and climate change.
It is the reason why they will need an increasing involvement in the coming weeks, both in terms of identifying priorities, both active and passive voters, considering that even at European level the average age of the Italian elect continues to be high, about 49.2 years. A trend that must be reversed, considering the wide will of young generations to be fully included in the decision-making processes to address what are, in their opinion, the major criticalities that live and which indicate with particular clarity as urgency and priority”.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

